{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599534"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:56:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:56:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15576"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15576"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8267"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66622"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8267"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52075"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8705"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22233"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66622"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, the thyroid gland descends from the foramen caecum at the base of the tongue to its final position in the anterior neck, leaving behind an epithelial tract called the thyroglossal duct.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the fate of the thyroglossal duct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It persists throughout life","Occasionally undergoes degeneration","Persistence may lead to cyst formation","Cyst formation is independent of persistence of duct","Degeneration is associated with sinus formation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe thyroglossal duct typically degenerates during normal development. If the duct fails to degenerate completely, remnants can form fluid-filled cavities known as thyroglossal duct cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that it\u003Cstrong\u003E persists throughout life\u003C/strong\u003E is not correct, as degeneration is more than \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccasional\u003C/strong\u003E and is the normal developmental process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroglossal cysts are uncommon (Image). They are midline structures, found immediately below the hyoid bone and do not move on swallowing.  When they do occur it is through the \u003Cstrong\u003Epersistence of the thyroglossal duct\u003C/strong\u003E. Cysts will not form independent of the duct. \u003Cstrong\u003ESinus formation\u003C/strong\u003E is uncommon and is associated with a persistent and patent duct.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The thyroglossal duct usually degenerates during embryological development, with failure of degeneration leading to thyroglossal duct cysts","The thyroid gland descends from the foramen caecum at the base of the tongue to its final position in the neck during development"],"references":["Moran C, Schoenmakers N, Visser WE, Schoenmakers E, Agostini M, Chatterjee K. Genetic disorders of thyroid development, hormone biosynthesis and signalling. Clin Endocrinol (Oxf). 2022 Oct;97(4):502-514. doi: 10.1111/cen.14817. Epub 2022 Sep 5. PMID: 35999191; PMCID: PMC9544560","Rosen RD, Sapra A. Embryology, Thyroid. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551611/","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press. USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52075"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15576"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21272"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21272"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/L1eKo8Ngb3SSS2teFMcxXehH544mh2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/L1eKo8Ngb3SSS2teFMcxXehH544mh2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":398,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52075"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T17:07:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T17:08:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8267"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66622"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"upd